#speculation(title: [Dual-Speed Decoupling May Explain the "Tired but Wired" Paradox])[
*Certainty: 0.20.* (Reduced from 0.25: the "pump running but drainage clogged" metaphor is inconsistent with the paper's own mechanism — LC-NE dysfunction impairs vasomotion, so the advective "pump" is already degraded. The corrected framing: both components decline together, but the *mismatch* between waste production and clearance generates the dissonance.) If ME/CFS involves impaired glymphatic clearance across both transport components (as the triple-hit model predicts), waste accumulates at the same time the brain is actively metabolizing. The resulting physiological dissonance — neuronal activity generating waste faster than even the surviving clearance capacity can remove it — may contribute to the "tired but wired" phenotype alongside the established orexin (Section @sec:ch15-orexin) and adenosine (Section @sec:ch15-adenosine) mechanisms. This is a convergent, not competing, mechanism: orexin deficiency and adenosine dysregulation generate the subjective experience of unrefreshing sleep; glymphatic impairment explains why that poor sleep fails to restore cognitive function.
] <spec:ch15-dual-speed-tired-wired>
